In 2014 two girls decided to go visit Panama, but unfortunately, they never returned to their home country. Some strange things happened, weird pictures were found, some personal material and bones. Today's case will talk about the disappearance of Dutch women Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon.

comments.text: My theory on what happened to Kris and Lisanne is this. The girls met with Henry Gonzalez stepson of Felicano and some of his friends earlier in the day, or the day before. When the girls came back down from the El Pianista trail ( which by the way is a well known drug trafficking trail) lots of drugs and dealers in Boqeute, the girls met up with Henry Gonzalez and his gang and went with them to swim in the Caldera hot springs that's where the photo was taken. Henry Gonzalez made a play for one of the girls I believe it was Lisanne, and she refused his advances, and Kris tried to protect Lisanne but the Henry and the others took them to a hideout and kept them there where the girls were se abused, Kris fought back and was hit in the head or in the jaw, she was killed before Lisanne, then when they had no further use for Lisanne she to was killed, they were both dismembered and the bones were buried, they had tried to dissolve some of the bones, and later on they planted a few of the bones so they could be found, and it would look like the girls got lost and died in the jungle. Henry Gonzalez is the only remaining member of the gang, the others including the taxi driver who dropped them off at the start of the trail died in mysterious circumstances, and 1 of the gang so say was a victim of a hit and run, but was repeatedly run over by the vehicle. They were basically silenced on the orders of Henry Gonzalez because he believed they would talk. It is believed that one of the gang refused to take part in the killing of the girls, and I think he was the first to die. Felicano knows what happened to Kris and Lisanne, but he is covering up for Henry, on the trail with Kris's parents he is heard and seen on camera telling one of the other guides to keep quiet and say nothing. I believe this was planned before the girls got to Boqeute, and that's the reason why they were turned away by the school. Miriam was friends with Felicano Gonzalez, so he would have known that the girls were coming to volunteer at school. Put another way, what Felicano doesn't know about Boqeute isn't worth knowing. And let's not forget 29 year old Alex Humphrey who went backpacking in Boqeute in August 2009 and checked into a hostel and has never been seen since, and no trace of belongings or bones have ever been found. Its like he vanished into thin air.

comments.text: My theory after spending hours and hours of watching videos about this case is this: They went to the top of the hill, then returned back to the village. People that saw them claimed it was later in the day and it would be possible to climb the hill and come back just in the time to be spotted by locals on their way back. Some even say they were taken by a car by some local guys. Those local guys? The son of guide F and his friends. They took the girls to the waterfalls since they were interested in seeing them and we can also see proof of that on the photo from the Gonzales' phone. Two guys from the gang (later found dead) and two women: one redhead, the other, although in the water with just her head and torso sticking out, clearly taller than the other woman. Froon was 184 cm tall, how many women in Panama and so white-skinned do you see in Panama regularly? not many. I am convinced they are in that photo. Later they tried to harvest their organs or kill them, we will probably never know, but that is when the girls tried to run away, or at least one of them managed to. All alone in the forest, not knowing the road back to the village, they/she was using the camera to light the way in front of her while being followed. Maybe it was both of them, maybe they left both phones in one backpack that only one of them now had with her and was trying to call 911....she later gets caught, killed...her personal belongings were looked through and they found an incriminating photo so they connected the phone to the pc and deleted it. That's why so many fingerprints have been found on the phone and other stuff. Later when the case got a huge press coverage some of the guys from the gang started backing out, being suspicious and guide F and his son were afraid they might tell something so they killed all the witnesses. This is the theory that makes the most sense to me.

Firstly it's not an easy trail. To people who have hiked it before, sure, but there are plenty of areas where one could take a wrong turn and yes there are dangerous areas on it where one could fall and get seriously injured. So yeah it is quite dangerous to walk it for the first time without a map & compass, without a guide and without GPS, with half charged phones. However it likely would have been fine had they simply walked back once they reached the top. 

The disastrous decision they made was to carry on down an unknown path. Likely they were on a high and wanted to carry on exploring but that's a very dangerous thing to do considering how ill prepared they were. They clearly got lost and most likely one of them at least got injured and they carried on hiking deeper and deeper into the jungle, tragically sealing their fate. The photos on their camera prove at least one of them was alive and that the other girl was at least there with her, several days after their disappearance so the talk of foul play is nonsense. As for why they'd take the pics, it's either for light, or because they thought they heard someone nearby and wanted to get their attention or because they're utterly deranged at this point and their actions make little sense. 

People want to turn this tragedy into some spooky conspiracy murder when actually, all the evidence points to two girls getting lost and drying in the jungle. Let it rest.

comments.text: It seems we are closer than ever before to finding what actually happened. The only way to know is to first find the night location where the pictures were taken in a hope to reconstruct the most logical path taken from there back to the trail. There is a general location which is being hypothesized as the most likely, which is on one of the rivers in a large valley that is to the East of the trail. It looks like the most likely thing that happened was the girls went pretty far down the other side of the mirador, but not all the way to the monkey bridges. It's not exactly clear how far they went, because they could have also taken a long stop by one of the streams, for example. The important part is that by the time they decided to head back they no longer had enough time to make the full trail before they lost visibility on the track due to the sun going down. On April 1st, the sun would go down fully roughly around 6:40 pm, though the girls didn't have that long. The trail would be enveloped by darkness considerably earlier than that since the sun would be blocked out by the mountains at some point, and only a portion of that light would make it thru the dense canopy of the forest. Anyone that's been in a forest during sunset knows what I mean; it can still be really bright outside the treeline but as soon as you start walking deeper in it feels like the sun has completely went down. It is likely that due to this, they left the trail and ended up finding a river that starts around this point, about half-way back up to the Mirador. If they went the West on that river, the direction of the trail they came from, they would find their path blocked by a large 10 meter high waterfall, which they couldn't realistically scale. This means it is more likely that they decided to follow the river East instead of going back into the jungle and trying to retrace their steps to the trail. Eventually that river turns into a series of rapids and smaller cascading waterfalls, which they would be on the top end of. Since there was barely any water in the river on April 1st, there is a good chance they tried making their way further down so they could continue following the river. It is likely one of them got hurt at this point, probably Lisanne, whose ankle showed that it was broken in three places. They continued a while further but at a certain point stopped and set up that camp we saw in the night photos. This would be April 8th so they would both be exhausted and hungry from not eating for a week at this point. Lisanne also had an infection from an inflamed femur which suggested she had been walking for a very long time, so it is less likely that the injury occurred very early on into the trip. It's likely Kris carried Lisanne for a while but she too eventually became exhausted from the lack of food. They most likely stayed in that night location where they set up the SOS signal and the reflective surface which was the bottom of a pringles can. The flag/marker they made was most likely at first a red bag over a branch which later got torn and became what we see in the photo. Kris and Lisanne seemed to be in a small area that provided some shelter from the rain, like a little cove at the bottom of an embankment where a steep hill meets the river shore. The flag was just tall enough to stick up over a boulder if leaned against it, which is probably where they left it when they were sleeping in case searchers were walking down the river and didn't see them. No one has searched this area yet as it is pretty far away and really dangerous to cross during wet seasons due to the strong currents. It doesn't seem anyone searched that river at all in time to have saved the girls either, but a Dutch team did go down that river in 2015 only to stop at the rapids/waterfalls. Kris and Lisanne couldnt have realistically made their way back up those falls either once they got down, especially if one of them was badly injured at that point. The area the night photos were taken also must flood during the wet season which explains why their remains and belongings were carried further down the river a few months later.

In the end, I think they let themselves be trapped by the arrival of night.
After photo 508, I think Lisanne dropped her camera on the ground or in the water. Making it unusable. Despite everything, they continued a little on the trail and at one point they decided to go back but they saw that the light was dropping very quickly in certain portions since we are in the tropics and the sun rises at 6:00 in the morning and goes to bed at 6:00 p.m. all year round.
They are therefore on their way back but they realize that they need at least two or three hours of walking and a large part of this walk will have to take place at night. They worry because they know the places they have already passed and know that without a flashlight, in the dark of night, it is very difficult and distressing.
Thats when they try to call for help, if only to say where they are because they didnt tell anyone in the end. They just said they were going for a walk.
But impossible to contact anyone: no network.
At that moment, they were not injured, nor pursued by anyone, just anxious at the idea of returning at night. The wisest thing would have been to land somewhere in open ground and resolve to spend the night there and leave the next morning at first light. In a video, the mother of Kriss who came on the trail explains that she is absolutely sure that if one of the girls had been injured, they would have stayed on the trail and waited. The problem actually is that he There was no injury or other, only from being trapped by the time and the arrival of night, and also from not having warned anyone.

I think that by trying to retrace the path at night, she had a high chance of getting lost, falling, slipping, etc. Which at night reinforces the seriousness of the situation.
So they get lost. And the second catastrophe arrives, no one knows where they went or more precisely, no one knows that they continued beyond the Mirador, towards the North on the path. So by the time we organize the research, a lot of time will pass. And we will have to wait until April 6 for research to be done on the other side of the Mirador. That is to say that the girls got lost, that they continued to move during these 6 days, if only to try to find a place with a little network. This is an interesting and well researched video, it seems to me. The theories are coherent and convincing as they are apparently backed up by solid evidence. 
But why does the voice-over have an English accent? The numbers 508, 510 etc. are read the American way. In Britain, when I lived there, at any rate, 508 would be pronounced 'five hundred and eight'. There are other weird things like 'only eight days later of the disappearance'. A person who has a good command of English would say  'only eight days after the disappearance'. comments.text:
They got lost 100% (I excuse for a certain length of the following comment)

Why would a perpetrator wait so long ? A Jungle at night is pitch black, you cant see your own hand, its that dark. So if there was someone he would have lead them into the forest, killed them and then would have taken their belongings to a place no one would look for, all in daylight, the forest would make it possible. 

In the night, there is a high chance the perpetrator himself would not be able to orientate very well and get lost himself, especially considering how far in they already were...its just unnecessary. 

Its much much much more likely they got lost:
To me it seems Kris was the more naive one, doesnt want to carry a backpack, is always walking in front and seems very curious overall. 
They both were highly unexperienced with the terrain, underprepared in regard to equipment and ill informed about a route that was difficult to navigate even for locals. I mean they both came from a highly urbanised country...the weather was very nice that day and overall there is a trail that they can follow....why not just walk a bit further down the path and see what we can find (maybe they heard rumors about secret places or stuff like that). The photos implicate a certain light hearted attitude. On the last daytime photo Kris does look a bit uncertain tho, no bright smile like in the other photos. I think at that point they realized they got lost but didnt panic or think of any mortal consequences. After that daytime photos stop, probably because at that point there were way more important things to do than take silly photos (search network connection, try to orientate, make waypoints etc.) 

Then come the nighttime photos. These got analyzed in depth (you cant really get more out of these at this point) and the overall concensus is that they tried to either orientate or more probably to signal their location, hence a lot of them are at the same spot and directed in the sky. At that point panic had set in for sure. Anyone who got lost once in a forest knows that panic sets in faster and faster the lower the sun sets, I cant imagine how horrified I would be in a south american jungle with all the animal noises plus being dehydrated and disoriented. 

I think Kris was the first who couldnt move forward at some point, possibly due to an injury like a fracture from a fall (the terrain would make that easy especially at night and panicked)
I think Lisanne was the more collected one, making almost all the photos and trying to use Kris phone.
Lisanne did sustain a injury herself, evident by the fracture on the foot that was found. 
First Kris was unable to move, Lisanne tried to call for help and at some point had an accident herself, so that both of them succumbed to the elements. Rain and the small river scattered their remains.
